WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:11.000
What does the word meaning denote in the expression meaning of life?

00:11.000 --> 00:17.000
Is it a directive, a feeling, or something else entirely?

00:17.000 --> 00:24.000
Well, I think it's not a straightforward manner to discuss the meaning of life, right?

00:24.000 --> 00:27.000
Because it's pretty clear that there are multiple meanings,

00:27.000 --> 00:31.000
and those meanings are associated with different events and situations.

00:31.000 --> 00:36.000
I think you can still intelligently address the issue of the meaning of life,

00:36.000 --> 00:41.000
because meanings tend to arrange themselves into a hierarchy of value and relevance,

00:41.000 --> 00:48.000
and they have to do that because otherwise there's nothing but, as William James suggested,

00:48.000 --> 00:51.000
sort of a blooming and buzzing confusion.

00:51.000 --> 00:56.000
So the issue is multiple meanings in a unified, integrated framework.

00:56.000 --> 01:01.000
Meaning is partly an impetus for action.

01:01.000 --> 01:06.000
It's very important to remember that human beings are active and living creatures,

01:06.000 --> 01:10.000
and that one of our primary problems, in fact, perhaps our primary problem,

01:10.000 --> 01:12.000
is how to act in the world.

01:12.000 --> 01:18.000
But that also involves other questions like how to perceive, how to prepare for action,

01:18.000 --> 01:21.000
how to plan for action in the future.

01:21.000 --> 01:25.000
And so all of those questions are associated with meaning.

01:25.000 --> 01:30.000
For me, meaning is the abstract impetus towards action, fundamentally.

01:30.000 --> 01:33.000
And it's an important thing to give some consideration to,

01:33.000 --> 01:40.000
because part of the Western intellectual tradition tends to abstract rationality

01:40.000 --> 01:45.000
or consciousness from embodiment, and it's very much the case that we are embodied creatures.

01:45.000 --> 01:49.000
The idea that our brain is in our head and that our mind is in our brain,

01:49.000 --> 01:57.000
it's a useful idea for certain purposes, but it obscures much while shedding light on other things.

01:57.000 --> 02:03.000
So meaning is tightly associated with action, with the abstraction of action,

02:03.000 --> 02:07.000
but then also with the construction of the perceptual frameworks and emotional responses

02:07.000 --> 02:14.000
that are necessary to conceive of the world in a manner that allows you to act in it.

02:14.000 --> 02:18.000
So one of the things we know, for example, is that when you walk into a room like this

02:18.000 --> 02:23.000
and you see the furniture of the landscape arrayed in front of you,

02:23.000 --> 02:28.000
that one of the things that you directly perceive is actually the meaning of that furniture.

02:28.000 --> 02:31.000
And you might think that you see the object and infer the meaning,

02:31.000 --> 02:36.000
and that's what you would think if you were a traditional Western rationalist or even a materialist,

02:36.000 --> 02:40.000
but it actually seems to be the case that when you walk into a room like this,

02:40.000 --> 02:45.000
the room tells you what to do at a level that's below conscious realization,

02:45.000 --> 02:48.000
and it's partly because, well, you know exactly what chairs are for.

02:48.000 --> 02:51.000
You might ask yourself, for example, what is a chair?

02:51.000 --> 02:55.000
It's a complicated question because it could be a beanbag and it could be a stump,

02:55.000 --> 02:58.000
but fundamentally a chair is something to sit in,

02:58.000 --> 03:04.000
and when you see a chair, the chair tells you directly as a perceptual consequence that you sit in it,

03:04.000 --> 03:06.000
and that's the meaning of the chair.

03:06.000 --> 03:13.000
And so you can't understand meaning in that manner without considering meaning in relationship to embodiment.

03:13.000 --> 03:17.000
And so meaning is really how we propel ourselves through the world

03:17.000 --> 03:21.000
and how we organize ourselves and arrange to propel ourselves through the world

03:21.000 --> 03:28.000
in a manner that's productive, relatively free of suffering, even though that's a meaning,

03:28.000 --> 03:32.000
and sustainable across many situations and contexts.

03:32.000 --> 03:36.000
So that's a rough framework for the initiation of the discussion.

03:39.000 --> 03:44.000
For me, I think the first thing I would say is that word meaning is being used as a metaphor.

03:44.000 --> 03:50.000
We're taking basically a term from language, a sentence is meaningful,

03:50.000 --> 03:57.000
and we're using it metaphorically to try to denote something that is probably pre-linguistic,

03:57.000 --> 03:59.000
although it shows up in our language.

03:59.000 --> 04:03.000
A sentence is meaningful in that it does something to information

04:03.000 --> 04:08.000
in such a way that we get a fundamental connection between ourselves and the world.

04:08.000 --> 04:13.000
And I think that's, for me, what is fundamentally going on when we talk about meaning.

04:13.000 --> 04:18.000
We're talking about the fact that there's a fundamental process of selection

04:18.000 --> 04:23.000
that the brain, the embodied brain, which I agree with you is a very important thing

04:23.000 --> 04:26.000
to constantly remind ourselves of, has to face.

04:26.000 --> 04:29.000
There's way too much information available at all times,

04:29.000 --> 04:36.000
and of all of that information, only some of it is going to be useful or helpful to an organism.

04:36.000 --> 04:39.000
And somehow that information has to be found.

04:39.000 --> 04:42.000
It has to be found in a very reliable manner.

04:42.000 --> 04:49.000
It has to be transformed into a form that is relevant to this body in this world,

04:49.000 --> 04:57.000
such that I can frame problems, solve problems, achieve my goals.

04:57.000 --> 05:03.000
And that process of zeroing in on relevant information, what I call relevance realization,

05:03.000 --> 05:11.000
means that we are fundamentally thrown into a atmospheric kind of relationship to the world.

05:11.000 --> 05:16.000
There's a salience landscape constantly being projected at all times of how things stand out to you,

05:16.000 --> 05:22.000
what gathers your attention, what arouses your metabolic resources or dampens them,

05:22.000 --> 05:26.000
what creates certain motivational and affective states.

05:26.000 --> 05:32.000
Because this relevance realization process is not a cold calculation, like a computer.

05:32.000 --> 05:37.000
It's instead a deep involvement between the organism and its world.

05:37.000 --> 05:44.000
And that involvement has, as Jordan says, it's often and most prominently going on below consciousness,

05:44.000 --> 05:47.000
and it's an ongoing, evolving process.

05:47.000 --> 05:49.000
I mean, one minute something is salient.

05:49.000 --> 05:52.000
Look, that became salient to you, now it's not salient anymore.

05:52.000 --> 05:54.000
So that process is constantly evolving.

05:54.000 --> 05:57.000
And so we shouldn't think of meaning as a static thing,

05:57.000 --> 06:02.000
but this ongoing process by which the organism is constantly fitting itself to the world

06:02.000 --> 06:08.000
and having the world fitted to it so that its actions can be undertaken in a fluent manner.

06:08.000 --> 06:12.000
Now the thing that I think is very important about this,

06:12.000 --> 06:17.000
meaning making process, or as I prefer to call it, relevance realization,

06:17.000 --> 06:20.000
because I think meaning is standing in as a metaphor for that,

06:20.000 --> 06:27.000
is that this process is, it's below our consciousness, it's below our rationality,

06:27.000 --> 06:31.000
it's below our language use, it's below our deliberative reasoning,

06:31.000 --> 06:35.000
precisely because it's constitutive or presupposed by all those processes.

06:35.000 --> 06:38.000
Until you do relevance realization, you can't use a language.

06:38.000 --> 06:41.000
Until you do relevance realization, you can't form representations.

06:41.000 --> 06:46.000
Until you do relevance realization, you can't even form your own autobiographical identity.

06:46.000 --> 06:53.000
The world as a place that has categories and you as a cognitive agent with a sense of identity in it,

06:53.000 --> 06:56.000
both co-spring from this relevance realization.

06:56.000 --> 07:00.000
It is a deep binding of you and the world at a fundamental level.

07:00.000 --> 07:03.000
And that's why when it's threatened in any fashion,

07:03.000 --> 07:09.000
human beings will experience a deep kind of trauma, absurdity, horror, a deep kind of anxiety.

07:09.000 --> 07:12.000
And so when I think people are talking about meaning in life,

07:12.000 --> 07:15.000
what they're trying to gesture towards is they have structures in place

07:15.000 --> 07:21.000
that maintain and enhance that relevance realization such that two things are possible.

07:21.000 --> 07:26.000
They can reliably keep at bay absurdity and horror,

07:26.000 --> 07:32.000
and they can reliably afford the ongoing evolution, the growth of that relevance realization

07:32.000 --> 07:36.000
so that they can find some kind of fulfillment in that identity

07:36.000 --> 07:39.000
that they are cultivating for themselves as a cognitive agent

07:39.000 --> 07:43.000
and the world into which they are fitted.

07:43.000 --> 07:46.000
And so I think the degree to which people are talking about meaning in life

07:46.000 --> 07:49.000
is the degree to which they're talking about those kinds of structures

07:49.000 --> 07:55.000
that affect that co-creation out of relevance realization of cognitive agency

07:55.000 --> 08:00.000
and a world in which cognitive agents can solve problems in an intelligible manner.

08:00.000 --> 08:05.000
We should also maybe decide if we agree on something.

08:05.000 --> 08:08.000
We're going to agree on many things, I suppose.

08:08.000 --> 08:12.000
And a lot of a discussion like this is often terminological

08:12.000 --> 08:14.000
and it's partly going to be the case between John and I

08:14.000 --> 08:17.000
because his intellectual background is different than mine,

08:17.000 --> 08:19.000
although it overlaps in some important ways.

08:19.000 --> 08:23.000
And so partly what I'm hoping to do with the discussion tonight

08:23.000 --> 08:26.000
is to make sure that we actually understand each other.

08:26.000 --> 08:29.000
This is definitely not a debate in which one of us is going to win.

08:29.000 --> 08:33.000
What we're hoping to do is to have the kind of conversation

08:33.000 --> 08:36.000
that allows for the scaffolding and the further development of ideas,

08:36.000 --> 08:39.000
which is really what an intellectual conversation is.

08:39.000 --> 08:42.000
So I want to offer you a couple of propositions

08:42.000 --> 08:44.000
and tell me what you think about them.

08:44.000 --> 08:47.000
The first thing is that I don't believe that the question

08:47.000 --> 08:50.000
does life have meaning is actually a reasonable question.

08:50.000 --> 08:52.000
I don't think it's properly formulated.

08:52.000 --> 08:54.000
And the reason I believe that is because

08:54.000 --> 08:59.000
that isn't really what people want to know when they ask that question.

08:59.000 --> 09:01.000
Life has lots of meanings.

09:01.000 --> 09:03.000
The Buddhists would say that life is suffering.

09:03.000 --> 09:06.000
And you know, we might not think about suffering as meaning,

09:06.000 --> 09:08.000
but fundamentally it's anxiety and pain

09:08.000 --> 09:11.000
and with some disgust thrown in there maybe for good measure.

09:11.000 --> 09:13.000
And those are meanings.

09:13.000 --> 09:16.000
And even if you're nihilistic and you're not oriented towards

09:16.000 --> 09:19.000
a belief in some sort of ultimate meaning structure,

09:19.000 --> 09:21.000
that doesn't mean you can escape from the meaning of life.

09:21.000 --> 09:24.000
What it does mean is that the meaning of your life is misery,

09:24.000 --> 09:27.000
suffering, anxiety, and a real decrement and quality.

09:27.000 --> 09:31.000
So we're trapped inside the question of the meaning of life.

09:31.000 --> 09:33.000
There's no getting outside of it.

09:33.000 --> 09:35.000
You can say there's no ultimate meaning,

09:35.000 --> 09:37.000
but then you have to define ultimate.

09:37.000 --> 09:39.000
And then the other thing that I thought...

09:39.000 --> 09:41.000
So let me just make sure I got the first proposition.

09:41.000 --> 09:43.000
The first proposition is the question,

09:43.000 --> 09:45.000
I want to make sure I got your wording right,

09:45.000 --> 09:47.000
does life have a meaning as opposed?

09:47.000 --> 09:49.000
I just want to store that.

09:49.000 --> 09:52.000
I can either respond or wait until you put your second question out.

09:53.000 --> 09:55.000
Yeah, yeah.

09:55.000 --> 09:57.000
I just don't want to lose the first question.

09:57.000 --> 10:00.000
The other thing that might be useful, clarifying,

10:00.000 --> 10:03.000
I understand what you mean by relevance realization.

10:03.000 --> 10:07.000
I have a formulation of it in my own language,

10:07.000 --> 10:10.000
so I'm going to make a couple of comments on that as well,

10:10.000 --> 10:13.000
and you can tell me if you agree or disagree on that.

10:13.000 --> 10:16.000
So one of the things that's quite...

10:16.000 --> 10:20.000
One of the ways that you can approach the idea of meaning

10:20.000 --> 10:22.000
is by making a separate assumption

10:22.000 --> 10:25.000
about what the fundamental structures in the world are.

10:25.000 --> 10:27.000
I mean, materialists and empiricists

10:27.000 --> 10:29.000
tend to believe that the fundamental structures are,

10:29.000 --> 10:31.000
we'll say, atomic particles,

10:31.000 --> 10:34.000
even though we know we can go higher resolution than that.

10:34.000 --> 10:36.000
There's atomic particles and there's this space

10:36.000 --> 10:38.000
in which they're distributed,

10:38.000 --> 10:42.000
and what that means is that the combination of quantum particles,

10:42.000 --> 10:44.000
quantized particles plus space,

10:44.000 --> 10:49.000
allows for the array of physical entities in patterns.

10:49.000 --> 10:51.000
Like music is a pattern,

10:51.000 --> 10:55.000
and there seems to me that there's something profoundly similar

10:55.000 --> 10:58.000
about patterns and information,

10:58.000 --> 11:01.000
and it seems to me that what we experience as meaning

11:01.000 --> 11:05.000
is something like our interaction with information.

11:05.000 --> 11:07.000
Now, I just want to say one more thing about that.

11:07.000 --> 11:09.000
The problem with information in some sense

11:09.000 --> 11:11.000
is that there's too much of it.

11:11.000 --> 11:13.000
So one of the things you could say about life's meaning

11:13.000 --> 11:16.000
is that there's absolutely way too much of it.

11:16.000 --> 11:18.000
You can certainly experience that

11:18.000 --> 11:20.000
if you ever have an experience of awe,

11:20.000 --> 11:23.000
or even of overwhelming absurdity.

11:23.000 --> 11:26.000
Those are both quasi-religious experiences.

11:26.000 --> 11:30.000
So relevance realization is actually, as far as I can tell,

11:30.000 --> 11:32.000
it's the limitation of what's essentially

11:32.000 --> 11:35.000
an close to infinite field of information

11:35.000 --> 11:37.000
that's so rich that it can't be exhausted

11:37.000 --> 11:40.000
into a narrower form that's focal and useful

11:40.000 --> 11:43.000
for this particular time and this particular place

11:43.000 --> 11:45.000
for this particular set of activities.

11:45.000 --> 11:47.000
So it's a narrowing process.

11:47.000 --> 11:50.000
Yeah, okay, so I'll respond to the second thing first

11:50.000 --> 11:52.000
because that will actually help me to respond

11:52.000 --> 11:55.000
to your first question about the posing of the question.

11:55.000 --> 11:57.000
Yeah, I think that's a good way of putting it.

11:57.000 --> 11:59.000
Although I would want to emphasize

11:59.000 --> 12:02.000
that I don't think that process is just a selection process,

12:02.000 --> 12:04.000
it's an important transformation process

12:04.000 --> 12:08.000
because we do something to the information,

12:08.000 --> 12:11.000
and you made reference to this in the embodiment.

12:11.000 --> 12:14.000
It's not just that we have sort of passively taken in the information

12:14.000 --> 12:16.000
or selected it from the environment.

12:16.000 --> 12:20.000
We make the pieces, like you said, we find patterns.

12:20.000 --> 12:22.000
It's how the pieces are relevant to each other,

12:22.000 --> 12:24.000
how they're relevant to us.

12:24.000 --> 12:26.000
Again, and I'm trying to emphasize this,

12:26.000 --> 12:29.000
not just as some sort of cold calculation

12:29.000 --> 12:32.000
about that information, but a way in which...

12:32.000 --> 12:35.000
I mean, we say it like we make sense.

12:35.000 --> 12:38.000
It's constitutive of our cognitive agency.

12:38.000 --> 12:41.000
Just like our bodies take in matter,

12:41.000 --> 12:43.000
but they don't just select the matter,

12:43.000 --> 12:45.000
they transform it and restructure it,

12:45.000 --> 12:47.000
so we have the ability to operate in the world.

12:47.000 --> 12:49.000
Our minds don't just select the information,

12:49.000 --> 12:52.000
they take in it, they transform it and structure it,

12:52.000 --> 12:54.000
so analogous to our bodies,

12:54.000 --> 12:57.000
we gain skills and abilities to interact with that world

12:57.000 --> 12:59.000
from which that information was selected.

12:59.000 --> 13:03.000
That's why I think people love to watch bands improvise,

13:03.000 --> 13:05.000
because really what they're doing,

13:05.000 --> 13:07.000
especially if they're doing it collectively,

13:07.000 --> 13:09.000
is they're engaging in a collective process

13:09.000 --> 13:11.000
of the spontaneous transmutation of patterns.

13:11.000 --> 13:14.000
And I think the reason that people find that so deeply meaningful

13:14.000 --> 13:17.000
is because it is representation,

13:17.000 --> 13:20.000
like an ongoing abstract artistic representation.

13:20.000 --> 13:24.000
I think it's an exemplification of what we do in the world.

13:24.000 --> 13:26.000
That's right. I think one of the reasons why we like art

13:26.000 --> 13:28.000
is we play with the variance...

13:28.000 --> 13:31.000
We're playing in the Piagetian sense of playing,

13:31.000 --> 13:33.000
in the sense of developing our skills.

13:33.000 --> 13:36.000
We play with the relevance realization machinery for its own sake.

13:36.000 --> 13:38.000
But that allows me to go back to your...

13:38.000 --> 13:42.000
I think asking for the meaning of life,

13:42.000 --> 13:44.000
it carries with it sort of...

13:44.000 --> 13:46.000
even saying the meaning in life,

13:46.000 --> 13:50.000
it carries with it the presupposition that meaning is sort of there to be found,

13:50.000 --> 13:55.000
and it immediately steers us away from this ongoing process

13:55.000 --> 13:57.000
in which we're taking in information,

13:57.000 --> 14:00.000
transforming it, structuring it,

14:00.000 --> 14:02.000
altering ourselves, fitting to a world

14:02.000 --> 14:06.000
that is then also itself, restructuring itself, changing itself.

14:06.000 --> 14:09.000
And so there's this ongoing, evolving relationship.

14:09.000 --> 14:12.000
So one of the reasons why I don't like the question,

14:12.000 --> 14:16.000
the meaning of life, is it proposes a ready-made answer to be found.

14:16.000 --> 14:20.000
It presupposes a static thing to be discovered,

14:20.000 --> 14:22.000
or even a static relation to be realized.

14:22.000 --> 14:27.000
And it also carries with it the idea that...

14:27.000 --> 14:30.000
It's like, like you said,

14:30.000 --> 14:35.000
it's like there is an answer to a question that has been posed,

14:35.000 --> 14:39.000
when I don't think the issue facing us is a riddle

14:39.000 --> 14:43.000
or a question in that sense that some proposition will satisfy.

14:43.000 --> 14:45.000
I don't think there's anything that...

14:45.000 --> 14:47.000
I'm sorry, this will sound incredibly pretentious,

14:47.000 --> 14:49.000
but I'm being asked about, I think.

14:49.000 --> 14:50.000
I don't think there's anything...

14:50.000 --> 14:52.000
I'm trying to make him sound pretentious.

14:52.000 --> 14:55.000
I don't think there's a proposition that anybody can say to you

14:55.000 --> 14:57.000
that will render your life meaningful.

14:57.000 --> 15:00.000
I mean, you might do things with that proposition

15:00.000 --> 15:03.000
that might fit you better to the world

15:03.000 --> 15:06.000
so that horror becomes less prevalent

15:06.000 --> 15:08.000
and flourishing becomes more prominent.

15:08.000 --> 15:11.000
But to think that the answer is in the proposition

15:11.000 --> 15:16.000
is to misunderstand the role of propositions in our cognition.

15:16.000 --> 15:18.000
The propositional level is very high up

15:18.000 --> 15:22.000
and sits on many recursive levels of relevance realization

15:22.000 --> 15:27.000
that only at their very tip produce this kind of propositional processing.

15:27.000 --> 15:32.000
The meaning is much more our knowing how to interact with the world,

15:32.000 --> 15:37.000
knowing how to fit my hand to this glass is part of that process.

15:37.000 --> 15:40.000
And that's not based on sort of just...

15:40.000 --> 15:44.000
It's not primarily based on my beliefs about the glass.

15:44.000 --> 15:47.000
It's based on a much more complex dynamical system

15:47.000 --> 15:51.000
by which my body, my perception, the glass, the atmosphere

15:51.000 --> 15:53.000
are fitting together so that I can grasp the glass.

15:53.000 --> 15:56.000
So one of the things that I found interesting,

15:56.000 --> 15:59.000
I learned this, I think, mostly from Gibson,

15:59.000 --> 16:04.000
who wrote a book called...

16:04.000 --> 16:07.000
One of the things Gibson presupposes,

16:07.000 --> 16:11.000
he has a very interesting way of looking at the world

16:11.000 --> 16:15.000
and it's tied deeply into our fundamental presuppositions

16:15.000 --> 16:17.000
about the structure of reality

16:17.000 --> 16:20.000
because one of the big issues about meaning in some sense

16:20.000 --> 16:25.000
is whether it's fundamentally constitutive of reality

16:25.000 --> 16:28.000
or if it's what would you call an emergent property

16:28.000 --> 16:29.000
of something more fundamental.

16:29.000 --> 16:34.000
Now the answer to that question in part is exactly what do you mean by reality

16:34.000 --> 16:37.000
and also the question is also what do you mean by truth

16:37.000 --> 16:40.000
and this isn't Pontius Pilate's question,

16:40.000 --> 16:42.000
it's a whole different kind of question.

16:42.000 --> 16:47.000
Now the modern neuroscientists in some sense following Gibson

16:47.000 --> 16:50.000
make the claim that when you look at a glass like that

16:50.000 --> 16:54.000
that what happens in your brain is that the pattern of the glass

16:54.000 --> 16:57.000
maps itself onto the pattern of your gripping hand

16:57.000 --> 17:00.000
and that maps itself onto the pattern of pouring and drinking

17:00.000 --> 17:05.000
and that a lot of that happens potentially before or alongside

17:05.000 --> 17:09.000
your conscious perception of the glass as an object.

17:09.000 --> 17:13.000
So we know for example that there are people who claim to be blind

17:13.000 --> 17:16.000
who can still map objects onto their body.

17:16.000 --> 17:18.000
So that's called blind sight.

17:18.000 --> 17:23.000
So developing that idea, it's appeared to me

17:23.000 --> 17:27.000
that there's good evidence that what we see when we look at the world is meaning.

17:27.000 --> 17:32.000
We don't see objects and infer meaning, we see meaning and we infer objects

17:32.000 --> 17:35.000
and so then the question is well is the meaning real

17:35.000 --> 17:39.000
and then that answer to that is well what do you mean by real

17:39.000 --> 17:42.000
and it'll only take me a minute to lay this out.

17:42.000 --> 17:46.000
This starts to depend on whether you're a Darwinian or a Newtonian.

17:46.000 --> 17:50.000
If you're a Newtonian then the real thing is the material object

17:50.000 --> 17:54.000
and we also know that Newton in some important ways was wrong

17:54.000 --> 17:58.000
but if you're a Darwinian and you almost have to be a Darwinian

17:58.000 --> 18:03.000
I really don't see any escape from it unless you don't know what you're talking about fundamentally.

18:03.000 --> 18:12.000
There's reasons for that is that the thing that determines whether or not

18:12.000 --> 18:18.000
you're going to survive and propagate which is by the way the best solution

18:18.000 --> 18:22.000
you can possibly answer to the problem of life if you're a biological organism

18:22.000 --> 18:27.000
and you have a Darwinian philosophy, the question you're trying to answer is

18:27.000 --> 18:30.000
what is the appropriate meaning to perceive in each environment

18:30.000 --> 18:33.000
because that determines your action and your action

18:33.000 --> 18:37.000
the consequences of your action determines whether you survive and propagate

18:37.000 --> 18:41.000
and so if you take the question of meaning from a Darwinian perspective

18:41.000 --> 18:45.000
you can actually say as far as I can tell that the fundamental constituent elements

18:45.000 --> 18:48.000
at least of experience and perhaps of reality itself

18:48.000 --> 18:52.000
are the meanings that you perceive before you infer the object.

18:52.000 --> 18:57.000
Now that's a pretty radical ontological claim and I've never heard anyone else actually make it

18:57.000 --> 18:59.000
except for maybe the pragmatists.

18:59.000 --> 19:04.000
It's a variant of pragmatic philosophy but I've tried to wrap my head around that argument

19:04.000 --> 19:09.000
and see if I can destroy it but I can't so I'm just wondering what you think about that.

19:09.000 --> 19:12.000
I have a lot to think about that and I have a lot to say about it.

19:12.000 --> 19:18.000
First of all, before I get into the Darwinian Newtonian thing

19:18.000 --> 19:21.000
which I've seen you do a couple of times before and I've always found it very interesting.

19:21.000 --> 19:23.000
It's one of my little tricks.

19:23.000 --> 19:27.000
You belittle it, it's one of your good tricks. I mean it's a very good one.

19:27.000 --> 19:29.000
It's a very good point.

19:29.000 --> 19:34.000
First of all the question, I do think that fittedness to the world does create

19:34.000 --> 19:41.000
