20:22.000 --> 20:24.000
such that it would destroy the relationship

20:24.000 --> 20:27.000
and almost all of them put their hands back up again.

20:29.000 --> 20:36.000
They would rather have the truth than have all of that other stuff that they find so good be illusory.

20:36.000 --> 20:39.000
And I think that was one of Plato's profound insights.

20:39.000 --> 20:43.000
This connectedness to reality is a fundamental drive in us.

20:43.000 --> 20:47.000
You know John, when you're asking that you're basically asking people whether or not

20:47.000 --> 20:51.000
if they were in a perfect garden they'd be willing to check out the snake.

20:51.000 --> 20:52.000
Yes, right.

20:52.000 --> 20:56.000
And the answer of course we all know is that well of course people will check out the snake

20:56.000 --> 20:58.000
because that's just what we're like.

20:58.000 --> 21:00.000
But I do think there's something important to that.

21:00.000 --> 21:04.000
I think ultimately the platonic orientation towards truth

21:04.000 --> 21:07.000
is grounded in that notion of a deeper drive towards real.

21:07.000 --> 21:12.000
I think asking the question about whether or not meaning is real

21:12.000 --> 21:16.000
part of it I want to challenge the presupposition behind the question first

21:16.000 --> 21:20.000
because the presupposition behind that is that only things are real

21:20.000 --> 21:23.000
and that relationships, relations between things aren't real.

21:23.000 --> 21:28.000
And I think it is very, so it might strike people as odd for me to say

21:28.000 --> 21:31.000
yes of course I think relevance is real

21:31.000 --> 21:34.000
I don't think it's part, and this is where I might differ with you

21:34.000 --> 21:35.000
but I think we'll have to negotiate it.

21:35.000 --> 21:39.000
I don't think it's part of the physical fabric of the universe

21:39.000 --> 21:43.000
nor do I think it is just a subjective illusion on our head.

21:43.000 --> 21:47.000
It is a real relation between us and the environment.

21:47.000 --> 21:53.000
Just like evolution is a real relation between an organism and its environment.

21:53.000 --> 21:55.000
It's not a property of the environment.

21:55.000 --> 21:57.000
It's not a property of the organism.

21:57.000 --> 22:02.000
It's a real relation between them that explains both the history of the organism

22:02.000 --> 22:04.000
and the history of the environment.

22:04.000 --> 22:06.000
So that would be a lovely thing to see if we can get clear

22:06.000 --> 22:11.000
because that's a very profound argument, like a profound debate.

22:11.000 --> 22:15.000
There are Heideggerians who took opposite positions on that.

22:15.000 --> 22:16.000
Yes, I'm aware of that.

22:16.000 --> 22:18.000
And some of them were psychologists, right?

22:18.000 --> 22:21.000
And so I'm just going to outline it for the audience

22:21.000 --> 22:23.000
and to make sure we're thinking about it the same way.

22:23.000 --> 22:27.000
One stance is that meaning, so to speak,

22:27.000 --> 22:32.000
is a consequence of the operation of these elaborate patterns of construction

22:32.000 --> 22:35.000
in your mind and that you're imposing that on the world.

22:35.000 --> 22:36.000
So it's like a structure issue.

22:36.000 --> 22:38.000
Yeah, that's a romantic issue with meaning.

22:38.000 --> 22:42.000
And then the other one is that meaning is in the world, so to speak,

22:42.000 --> 22:45.000
and that what you do with the structures in your head is limited and narrow it.

22:45.000 --> 22:49.000
And I think in some weird way both of those things are true.

22:49.000 --> 22:53.000
But here's something that I've been thinking about for a long time

22:53.000 --> 22:57.000
and I want you to maybe help me figure out a bit more.

22:57.000 --> 23:02.000
So I'm going to go at this from two perspectives.

23:02.000 --> 23:05.000
So back in the late 1800s,

23:05.000 --> 23:09.000
Nietzsche basically formalized a set of observations

23:09.000 --> 23:11.000
about what he thought was happening in Western society

23:11.000 --> 23:13.000
and then the world at large, right?

23:13.000 --> 23:15.000
And the basic argument was something like this,

23:15.000 --> 23:18.000
was that the metaphysical presuppositions of religious systems

23:18.000 --> 23:22.000
and the metaphysical presuppositions of scientific systems were not in sync.

23:22.000 --> 23:24.000
They weren't of the same paradigm.

23:24.000 --> 23:28.000
And that as Western scientific investigation had preceded,

23:28.000 --> 23:34.000
it became obvious that either the truths of religion weren't true

23:34.000 --> 23:38.000
or at least that they weren't of the type that science recognized as truth.

23:38.000 --> 23:41.000
And Nietzsche basically described that as the death of God.

23:41.000 --> 23:45.000
And so he said that three things would happen in the aftermath of that.

23:46.000 --> 23:49.000
He was a prophet. He was like an Old Testament prophet.

23:49.000 --> 23:55.000
He said that totalitarianism would become unbelievably attractive to people,

23:55.000 --> 23:59.000
especially in its hyper-socialist variants like communism,

23:59.000 --> 24:03.000
and that millions of people would die in the 20th century as a consequence of that

24:03.000 --> 24:05.000
and that it would be a necessary battle.

24:05.000 --> 24:08.000
And he said that like 40 years before the Russian Revolution

24:08.000 --> 24:10.000
and so like, yeah, go Nietzsche.

24:10.000 --> 24:14.000
You try to predict the future like five years ahead, see how far you get.

24:14.000 --> 24:21.000
And then the other thing he said would be that nihilism would rise to pathological proportions

24:21.000 --> 24:24.000
because it's basically the polar opposite of totalitarianism, right?

24:24.000 --> 24:26.000
You wipe out the religious structures.

24:26.000 --> 24:29.000
People move towards ideology to reattain that certainty,

24:29.000 --> 24:34.000
but it's rigid and deadly, or they fall off into chaos itself.

24:34.000 --> 24:38.000
Okay, then Nietzsche made one more proposition which was that

24:39.000 --> 24:44.000
the only solution to that would be for human beings to transform themselves

24:44.000 --> 24:47.000
into meaning-creating creatures.

24:47.000 --> 24:51.000
And so what Nietzsche basically did, and I think this was a mistake in his metaphysics,

24:51.000 --> 24:55.000
was that he assumed that the objective description of reality was correct,

24:55.000 --> 24:59.000
that reality in and of itself was dead and meaningless,

24:59.000 --> 25:02.000
but that human beings could interact with that in such a way

25:02.000 --> 25:06.000
as a consequence of their individual choices to make that richly meaningful.

25:06.000 --> 25:11.000
And that we needed to do that because the alternatives would be nihilism or totalitarianism.

25:11.000 --> 25:15.000
One more comment on that.

25:15.000 --> 25:19.000
So, you know, Jung was a student of Nietzsche, a profound student,

25:19.000 --> 25:22.000
and he was actually trying to solve the problem that Nietzsche put forward,

25:22.000 --> 25:25.000
which was, oh, wow, we got nihilism on the one hand

25:25.000 --> 25:27.000
and we got totalitarianism on the other hand,

25:27.000 --> 25:30.000
and, you know, those don't really seem to be very good solutions

25:30.000 --> 25:32.000
since millions of people die because of one

25:32.000 --> 25:35.000
and millions of people commit suicide because of the other.

25:35.000 --> 25:39.000
It's like those are suboptimal solutions in all likelihood.

25:39.000 --> 25:45.000
So, but Jung in some sense took issue with Nietzsche's fundamental proposition,

25:45.000 --> 25:49.000
which was that human beings were meaning creating creatures.

25:49.000 --> 25:53.000
And I actually think it's the most profound critique of Nietzsche

25:53.000 --> 25:58.000
because what Jung pointed out, this is something that just blew me away when I first understood it,

25:58.000 --> 26:03.000
and it has to do with your relevance realization issue in a deadly way.

26:03.000 --> 26:08.000
It's like, imagine the things that attract your attention and your interest.

26:08.000 --> 26:10.000
Well, okay, so then you might think,

26:10.000 --> 26:15.000
well, is that a voluntary process or an involuntary process?

26:15.000 --> 26:17.000
And to answer that, you can think about it.

26:17.000 --> 26:21.000
It's like you're working on some dismally wretched, boring,

26:21.000 --> 26:24.000
and stultifying thing at work or as a student,

26:24.000 --> 26:28.000
and your attention is like fragmented everywhere.

26:28.000 --> 26:30.000
You think about the dust bunnies under your bed

26:30.000 --> 26:32.000
and that maybe the dishes need to be done

26:32.000 --> 26:34.000
or maybe the rug needs to be walked

26:34.000 --> 26:36.000
and the rug needs to be vacuumed

26:36.000 --> 26:39.000
and it's like bloody well anything other than that boring task.

26:39.000 --> 26:43.000
Even though you know you have to do it in order to say pass a course

26:43.000 --> 26:45.000
or pass an exam or get the assignment done,

26:45.000 --> 26:47.000
you can't control your damn brain.

26:47.000 --> 26:49.000
It's wandering everywhere.

26:49.000 --> 26:52.000
And then, so the weird thing about that

26:52.000 --> 26:55.000
is that you cannot voluntarily control your relevance realization.

26:55.000 --> 26:57.000
And then you have the contrary problem,

26:57.000 --> 27:02.000
which is that there's a YouTube video about kittens

27:02.000 --> 27:05.000
and it's like bang man, you're focused on that.

27:05.000 --> 27:08.000
And so one of the things you might ask

27:08.000 --> 27:12.000
is just who the hell is in control of this relevance realization?

27:12.000 --> 27:14.000
And that was Jung's question.

27:14.000 --> 27:16.000
It was like, well where Nietzsche fell apart,

27:16.000 --> 27:19.000
Nietzsche fell apart was that he assumed that human beings

27:19.000 --> 27:22.000
were primarily meaning making creatures.

27:22.000 --> 27:24.000
But then if you try it, it's like,

27:24.000 --> 27:27.000
hey, I'm going to find it really meaningful to go to the gym

27:27.000 --> 27:29.000
three times a week next week for half an hour

27:29.000 --> 27:31.000
and I'm going to push myself right to my limits.

27:31.000 --> 27:33.000
It's like I have every reason for doing it.

27:33.000 --> 27:35.000
I know why I should do it,

27:35.000 --> 27:38.000
but I'd rather sit on the couch in my underwear and eat cheetes.

27:38.000 --> 27:40.000
Cheetos.

27:46.000 --> 27:49.000
So you've got to ask yourself, man, who's in charge.

27:49.000 --> 27:53.000
And one of the things that the psychodynamic theorists were so damn good at

27:53.000 --> 27:58.000
was pointing out that, well, you think it's you, but it's not.

27:58.000 --> 28:00.000
And so then that begs the question.

28:00.000 --> 28:04.000
It's like, where's the meaning coming from and who is in charge?

28:04.000 --> 28:07.000
And so I know that's questions that you're trying to answer,

28:07.000 --> 28:11.000
but it doesn't exactly seem to me that we're overlaying that on the world

28:11.000 --> 28:14.000
or that if we are, we don't have much voluntary control over that.

28:14.000 --> 28:17.000
Okay, well, I don't think we're overlaying it on the world

28:17.000 --> 28:19.000
and that's what I meant by a real relation

28:19.000 --> 28:21.000
and I was comparing it to evolution.

28:21.000 --> 28:26.000
I think to talk about us being meaning makers in the Nietzschean sense

28:26.000 --> 28:30.000
is to fall prey to the romantic illusion

28:30.000 --> 28:32.000
that the world is a blank slate.

28:32.000 --> 28:35.000
I mean, you have the blank slate of the enlightenment

28:35.000 --> 28:38.000
in which reason the world writes on us

28:38.000 --> 28:40.000
and then you have the blank slate of the romantics

28:40.000 --> 28:42.000
in which the world is a blank slate,

28:42.000 --> 28:45.000
like the unpainted canvas that we...

28:45.000 --> 28:49.000
And Nietzsche constantly used the artistic metaphor

28:49.000 --> 28:51.000
and even created the idea of a lifestyle

28:51.000 --> 28:54.000
as if our lives are works of art

28:54.000 --> 28:58.000
because the world is just an empty canvas upon which we project our meaning.

28:58.000 --> 29:01.000
Well, and there's totalitarian presuppositions in there too

29:01.000 --> 29:05.000
because one of the presuppositions of totalitarian ideologues

29:05.000 --> 29:07.000
is that there is no such thing as human nature

29:07.000 --> 29:10.000
and that people can be constructed in any way possible.

29:10.000 --> 29:13.000
Exactly, and that's why existentialism comes out of Nietzsche

29:13.000 --> 29:16.000
because existentialism posits that our essence and our nature

29:16.000 --> 29:18.000
is completely the property of our own self-definition.

29:18.000 --> 29:23.000
So what I'm actually doing is I'm rejecting both of those blank slates.

29:23.000 --> 29:25.000
I'm saying the world is neither a blank slate

29:25.000 --> 29:27.000
that we romantically project upon

29:27.000 --> 29:32.000
nor is the mind a blank slate that experience just empirically draws upon.

29:32.000 --> 29:37.000
What I'm proposing instead is a dynamic interaction between the two

29:37.000 --> 29:43.000
and to say that who's in charge is kind of an odd question

29:43.000 --> 29:45.000
but before I answer that,

29:45.000 --> 29:49.000
I want to take a little bit of exception on your interpretation of Nietzsche

29:49.000 --> 29:52.000
because I think it might help

29:52.000 --> 29:55.000
and it also might get us back to the Newton-Darwin thing

29:55.000 --> 29:57.000
which I promise to get back to too.

29:57.000 --> 30:03.000
I mean, Nietzsche lays, and again, Heidegger followed up on this,

30:03.000 --> 30:07.000
he actually lays the history of nihilism much further back.

30:07.000 --> 30:10.000
