31:12.000 --> 31:14.000
or John Lennon, right?

31:14.000 --> 31:16.000
Then we're left.

31:16.000 --> 31:17.000
My favorite beatle.

31:17.000 --> 31:19.000
We're left, right?

31:19.000 --> 31:21.000
That really dates me, doesn't it?

31:21.000 --> 31:25.000
Then we're left with this world that we've been tutored for millennia,

31:25.000 --> 31:28.000
has no value in it.

31:28.000 --> 31:32.000
And so I think what Nietzsche was trying to do,

31:32.000 --> 31:34.000
I agree with you, there's a romantic streak in Nietzsche

31:34.000 --> 31:36.000
and like I said, I reject that romantic streak

31:36.000 --> 31:40.000
that the world is a blank slate upon which we paint our lifestyles.

31:40.000 --> 31:43.000
That is ridiculously hubristic in nature.

31:43.000 --> 31:46.000
But there was another thing Nietzsche was trying to do,

31:46.000 --> 31:49.000
and so I think there's, I mean Nietzsche has multiple voices,

31:49.000 --> 31:50.000
it has anything.

31:50.000 --> 31:52.000
So in addition to the romantic project,

31:52.000 --> 31:54.000
which I often find really bombastic,

31:54.000 --> 31:58.000
there is another project that he called trying to revalue the earth,

31:58.000 --> 32:03.000
which was to try to see the earth as a place in which we could be at home.

32:04.000 --> 32:07.000
On its own terms, for its own sake.

32:07.000 --> 32:09.000
So that was more Heidegger, I think.

32:09.000 --> 32:14.000
No, no, Heidegger talks about learning how to revalue the earth

32:14.000 --> 32:18.000
and loving the earth as a repeated theme throughout Nietzsche's work,

32:18.000 --> 32:21.000
and loving the body is a repeated theme in Nietzsche's work.

32:21.000 --> 32:25.000
Because he thought that just like we had the two worlds,

32:25.000 --> 32:27.000
we had the two parts of us, we had the body,

32:27.000 --> 32:30.000
but the body only existed in service of the soul,

32:30.000 --> 32:33.000
and the body therefore has no inherent value,

32:33.000 --> 32:37.000
because its only job is to get the soul to the only place where it has real meaning,

32:37.000 --> 32:38.000
which is heaven.

32:38.000 --> 32:42.000
And then his point was, if we lose the heaven and if we lose the idea of the soul,

32:42.000 --> 32:46.000
we have to get back to revaluing the body, revaluing the earth.

32:46.000 --> 32:50.000
And what I'm proposing in this sort of evolutionary model of relevance realisation

32:50.000 --> 32:55.000
is exactly that the body and the earth co-create this real relation

32:55.000 --> 32:59.000
that fundamentally homes us and fits us into the world.

32:59.000 --> 33:03.000
And that the meaning crisis and therefore, it's not just...

33:03.000 --> 33:07.000
I mean, yes, I agree, there are definitely historical forces for it

33:07.000 --> 33:12.000
and the rise of science and the demise of the wisdom traditions and the religious traditions.

33:12.000 --> 33:15.000
But I think the meaning crisis is in some sense also a perennial problem.

33:15.000 --> 33:18.000
You see it cross-culturally, you see it cross-historically,

33:18.000 --> 33:22.000
because people can always get trapped between these two kinds of perspectives

33:22.000 --> 33:23.000
they can have on themselves.

33:23.000 --> 33:26.000
They can always fall prey to these kinds of two world models.

33:27.000 --> 33:30.000
And so I think the thing I want to say is

33:33.000 --> 33:38.000
part of what's going on right now in the meaning crisis in the West

33:38.000 --> 33:39.000
is we're trying to...

33:39.000 --> 33:42.000
And this is the way Nietzsche, I think, was prescient, as you said.

33:42.000 --> 33:44.000
He was a prophet.

33:44.000 --> 33:46.000
By the way, he predicted four things.

33:46.000 --> 33:48.000
