35:11.000 --> 35:14.000
But if you can push these sorts of things back,

35:14.000 --> 35:17.000
I think to the dawn of self-consciousness itself.

35:17.000 --> 35:20.000
And one of the reasons that I've been so obsessed with the book of Genesis

35:20.000 --> 35:26.000
is because I read Genesis as a dramatic representation

35:26.000 --> 35:29.000
of the coming to self-consciousness of mankind.

35:29.000 --> 35:32.000
Because what happens with Adam and Eve when they eat the fruit

35:32.000 --> 35:34.000
that the snake delivers to them,

35:34.000 --> 35:38.000
which is very interesting sort of phenomena from an evolutionary perspective,

35:38.000 --> 35:39.000
which I can talk about later,

35:39.000 --> 35:42.000
what happens to Adam and Eve is very, very specific.

35:42.000 --> 35:44.000
I mean, the first thing that happens...

35:44.000 --> 35:46.000
I'm sorry, I might get the order wrong.

35:46.000 --> 35:49.000
But the first thing that happens is that they realize

35:49.000 --> 35:51.000
their eyes are opened and they're like gods

35:51.000 --> 35:53.000
knowing the difference between good and evil.

35:53.000 --> 35:55.000
And that's very interesting,

35:55.000 --> 35:58.000
because it associates the development of self-consciousness

35:58.000 --> 36:02.000
and the rise of articulated and complicated morality.

36:02.000 --> 36:04.000
And so I've thought about that for a long time.

36:04.000 --> 36:06.000
It's like, okay, you realize you're naked.

36:06.000 --> 36:08.000
What does that mean?

36:08.000 --> 36:10.000
Well, you don't want to be naked up here on the stage,

36:10.000 --> 36:12.000
if you're speaking properly to the audience you are.

36:12.000 --> 36:14.000
But maybe you don't want that.

36:14.000 --> 36:15.000
Okay, well, why?

36:15.000 --> 36:17.000
Why don't you want to be up here naked on the stage?

36:17.000 --> 36:19.000
It's everyone's nightmare, right?

36:19.000 --> 36:22.000
Well, you know, you're kind of flawed and saggy,

36:22.000 --> 36:25.000
and there's parts of you that are not that beautiful,

36:25.000 --> 36:28.000
even if you happen to be a supermodel.

36:28.000 --> 36:30.000
And you're not as bright as you could be,

36:30.000 --> 36:32.000
and your hair might be going a little bit,

36:32.000 --> 36:34.000
and your teeth aren't that great,

36:34.000 --> 36:36.000
and you're not as smart as you could be,

36:36.000 --> 36:37.000
and you've got a lot of flaws,

36:37.000 --> 36:39.000
plus you're going to get sick, and then you're going to die.

36:39.000 --> 36:41.000
It's like, right, right.

36:41.000 --> 36:43.000
So that's all nakedness.

36:43.000 --> 36:46.000
If you think about nakedness as vulnerability.

36:46.000 --> 36:48.000
And so we had to come to terms with her vulnerability

36:48.000 --> 36:50.000
when we became self-conscious.

36:50.000 --> 36:51.000
So then you might think,

36:51.000 --> 36:53.000
well, what the hell does that have to do with morality?

36:53.000 --> 36:54.000
And I did figure that out.

36:54.000 --> 36:57.000
It took me like 15 years of thinking to figure that out.

36:57.000 --> 37:01.000
It's like, if I know I'm naked and vulnerable,

37:01.000 --> 37:04.000
and I know you are the same,

37:04.000 --> 37:06.000
then I know what will hurt me.

37:06.000 --> 37:08.000
And once I know what will hurt me,

37:08.000 --> 37:10.000
I know what will hurt you.

37:10.000 --> 37:12.000
And so animals prey on each other.

37:12.000 --> 37:14.000
Lions eat gazelles,

37:14.000 --> 37:17.000
and worms eat lions, and all of that.

37:17.000 --> 37:20.000
But there's nothing like a human being

37:20.000 --> 37:23.000
for sheer outright atrocious torture.

37:23.000 --> 37:25.000
And you don't get that without self-consciousness.

37:25.000 --> 37:28.000
So that's where I think the knowledge of good and evil comes.

37:28.000 --> 37:30.000
It's like it's no longer prey and predator.

37:30.000 --> 37:32.000
It's like torture and victim.

37:32.000 --> 37:34.000
So that's one thing.

37:35.000 --> 37:39.000
And part of that sets up this dichotomy in human beings

37:39.000 --> 37:42.000
between whatever it is that our consciousness seems to be

37:42.000 --> 37:44.000
and our self-consciousness,

37:44.000 --> 37:47.000
and this terrible, limited burden that we carry around

37:47.000 --> 37:49.000
as a body that we're conscious of.

37:49.000 --> 37:51.000
So there's that dichotomy.

37:51.000 --> 37:54.000
That dichotomy emerges back at the beginning

37:54.000 --> 37:56.000
of the dichotomy of self-consciousness.

37:56.000 --> 37:58.000
It's a problem we're trying to solve all the time.

37:58.000 --> 38:01.000
And I mean, Nietzsche's criticism of Christianity

38:01.000 --> 38:04.000
was that he believed that Christianity

38:04.000 --> 38:06.000
failed to solve that problem

38:06.000 --> 38:09.000
because instead of dealing with the reality of the catastrophe,

38:09.000 --> 38:12.000
which is, say, the degenerate form of our material body,

38:12.000 --> 38:15.000
the church basically damned that to perdition,

38:15.000 --> 38:18.000
describing it as a work of the devils, so to speak,

38:18.000 --> 38:21.000
and then concentrated on spiritual salvation.

38:21.000 --> 38:28.000
Now, you knew this element of Christian religious thought

38:28.000 --> 38:30.000
and the Nietzschean transformations of that,

38:30.000 --> 38:33.000
and that's part of the reason why he went back to alchemy,

38:33.000 --> 38:36.000
because one of the things Jung was interested in was

38:36.000 --> 38:38.000
why did science develop?

38:38.000 --> 38:41.000
It only developed in Europe as far as we know,

38:41.000 --> 38:43.000
and the Greeks didn't have it, and the Romans didn't have it,

38:43.000 --> 38:46.000
and the Chinese didn't have it, and the Indians didn't have it,

38:46.000 --> 38:48.000
and it's like, well, they weren't stupid.

38:48.000 --> 38:50.000
What was up with them and why Europe?

38:50.000 --> 38:52.000
What exactly happened there?

38:52.000 --> 38:54.000
It's not like we precisely know the answer to that,

38:54.000 --> 38:57.000
but one of the things that Jung suggested,

38:57.000 --> 38:59.000
and it's brilliant as far as I'm concerned,

39:00.000 --> 39:06.000
the cognitive apparatuses that we're blessed with are compensatory,

39:06.000 --> 39:09.000
so that if we formulate a theory about one domain

39:09.000 --> 39:11.000
and take it to a real extreme,

39:11.000 --> 39:17.000
the unconscious mind will start to formulate a counter proposition,

39:17.000 --> 39:20.000
which is formulated of all the things we notice

39:20.000 --> 39:22.000
that don't fit in with that theory,

39:22.000 --> 39:24.000
and then they start to flap around

39:24.000 --> 39:28.000
and associate with each other as a consequence of emotional contagion,

39:28.000 --> 39:31.000
and they start to manifest themselves in patterns,

39:31.000 --> 39:34.000
and that once that counter position emerges

39:34.000 --> 39:38.000
as a sufficiently complex and dynamic living system,

39:38.000 --> 39:41.000
it has the opportunity to fight with the other system,

39:41.000 --> 39:43.000
and sometimes you'll have a revelation,

39:43.000 --> 39:45.000
and the revelation is basically the overthrow

39:45.000 --> 39:48.000
of the current perspective by the new emergent perspective.

39:49.000 --> 39:52.000
Jung viewed alchemy in that light.

39:52.000 --> 39:56.000
He said that the Christian concentration on hyper-spiritualization

39:56.000 --> 39:58.000
was extremely useful, this is something Nietzsche agreed with,

39:58.000 --> 40:01.000
was unbelievably useful for the discipline of the mind,

40:01.000 --> 40:04.000
so Nietzsche, of course, is an anti-Christian,

40:04.000 --> 40:06.000
at least that's what he said,

40:06.000 --> 40:09.000
but he also said that Catholicism tempered the European spirit

40:09.000 --> 40:11.000
like nothing else could have,

40:11.000 --> 40:13.000
and he really meant the whole Judeo-Christian tradition,

40:13.000 --> 40:16.000
which was the attempt to force everything

40:16.000 --> 40:20.000
into a unified and hierarchically arranged interpretation.

40:20.000 --> 40:23.000
Nietzsche's idea was once you did that once, man,

40:23.000 --> 40:25.000
you could go do that all sorts of different places,

40:25.000 --> 40:30.000
so alchemy as a precursor to science

40:30.000 --> 40:33.000
was based initially on a fantasy,

40:33.000 --> 40:37.000
and the fantasy was if we paid enough attention

40:37.000 --> 40:41.000
to the transformations of matter rather than of spirit,

40:41.000 --> 40:44.000
that we could redeem what Christianity,

40:44.000 --> 40:47.000
with its emphasis on the spirit, had failed to redeem.

40:47.000 --> 40:50.000
So it was sort of like all the 14th century Europeans woke up

40:50.000 --> 40:53.000
and said, hmm, Christ died for our sins,

40:53.000 --> 40:55.000
and we're supposed to be redeemed,

40:55.000 --> 40:57.000
but a lot of guys are down there with leprosy in the ditch,

40:57.000 --> 41:01.000
so it doesn't seem to have exactly fulfilled its promise,

41:01.000 --> 41:03.000
and so he felt that the European imagination

41:03.000 --> 41:07.000
started to drift into the transformations of the material world,

41:07.000 --> 41:13.000
but that was also part of what was fundamentally a redemptive process.

41:13.000 --> 41:16.000
It was just a more comprehensive redemptive process.

41:16.000 --> 41:19.000
It was, all right, well, we kind of got the spirit organized,

41:19.000 --> 41:22.000
now it's time to do something about the dreadful body

41:22.000 --> 41:24.000
that we're dragging around with us

41:24.000 --> 41:26.000
instead of merely damning it to perdition.

41:26.000 --> 41:28.000
And one of the things that you might think about,

41:28.000 --> 41:31.000
because we're also thinking about practical issues here,

41:31.000 --> 41:35.000
is, well, we talked about multiple meanings,

41:35.000 --> 41:37.000
kind of multiple low-level meanings.

41:37.000 --> 41:39.000
There's the meaning of food and the meaning of water

41:39.000 --> 41:41.000
and the meaning of sex and, you know,

41:41.000 --> 41:43.000
the meaning of being too hot and too cold,

41:43.000 --> 41:45.000
and there's all biological subsystems

41:45.000 --> 41:47.000
that take care of those sorts of things.

41:47.000 --> 41:50.000
It's like those are organized hierarchically in principle,

41:50.000 --> 41:52.000
so there's something lurking at the top.

41:52.000 --> 41:55.000
And I think part of what religious mythologies do over years,

41:55.000 --> 41:57.000
centuries, thousands of years,

41:57.000 --> 42:01.000
is try to get a picture of what should be at the top.

42:01.000 --> 42:03.000
That's like the monotheistic impulse.

42:03.000 --> 42:05.000
What's the highest value?

42:05.000 --> 42:07.000
And here's something to consider.

42:07.000 --> 42:09.000
You know, you can wonder about this in your own lives

42:09.000 --> 42:11.000
when people think about the meaning of their life.

42:11.000 --> 42:16.000
What they mean is, are all the subsidiary meanings

42:16.000 --> 42:20.000
meaningful given that there's an ultimate reality

42:20.000 --> 42:22.000
of suffering and limitation.

42:22.000 --> 42:25.000
And so one of the things that might be asked,

42:25.000 --> 42:28.000
and I think that scientists do ask this in part,

42:28.000 --> 42:31.000
is maybe we shouldn't deal with that question

42:31.000 --> 42:35.000
before we fix everything we can possibly fix.

42:35.000 --> 42:37.000
And so one of the things that I would also suggest

42:37.000 --> 42:40.000
is that when you're motivated by meanings

42:40.000 --> 42:42.000
that are other than subsidiary,

42:42.000 --> 42:46.000
say the same meanings that animate mammals and reptiles

42:46.000 --> 42:49.000
and even bloody lobsters, for that matter,

42:49.000 --> 42:52.000
when you're working at higher-order levels of meaning,

42:52.000 --> 42:55.000
partly what you're attempting to do

42:55.000 --> 42:59.000
is to generate solutions to the micro-problems

42:59.000 --> 43:01.000
of negative meaning that always beset you.

43:01.000 --> 43:03.000
You know, it's like, well,

43:03.000 --> 43:05.000
is there something wrong in your family?

43:05.000 --> 43:07.000
Well, that's meaningful.

43:07.000 --> 43:09.000
The meaning is negative.

43:09.000 --> 43:12.000
So does that make your family worthwhile or worthless?

43:12.000 --> 43:14.000
Well, the question is,

43:14.000 --> 43:16.000
depends on what you do with your family.

43:16.000 --> 43:19.000
And you know, so the problem with nihilism,

43:19.000 --> 43:22.000
as far as I can tell, is that the nihilist presumes

43:22.000 --> 43:25.000
that the finitude that we perceive

43:25.000 --> 43:27.000
invalidates the utility of being.

43:27.000 --> 43:31.000
It's like, well, that's pretty arrogant, you might say.

43:31.000 --> 43:34.000
You might say that judging the whole world in that light,

43:34.000 --> 43:37.000
which is what that comedian just did on that TV show

43:37.000 --> 43:40.000
that he laid into God, I can't remember his name,

43:40.000 --> 43:42.000
blaming him for bone cancer and children, for example,

43:42.000 --> 43:44.000
which really does suck, you know.

43:44.000 --> 43:47.000
So the point is, is that one of the things

43:47.000 --> 43:50.000
that we find meaningful and we could find meaningful

43:50.000 --> 43:53.000
and that's reliable is,

43:53.000 --> 43:56.000
let's leave the damn question aside about the ultimate meaning

43:56.000 --> 43:59.000
of reality in its corrupt form, which is now,

43:59.000 --> 44:01.000
and try to fix the damn thing.

44:01.000 --> 44:03.000
Really try to fix it.

44:03.000 --> 44:05.000
And then see what happens,

44:05.000 --> 44:07.000
it's clear that we can make things better

44:07.000 --> 44:09.000
and it's bloody clear that we can make things worse,

44:09.000 --> 44:11.000
so you might ask, okay, well, if you organized

44:11.000 --> 44:14.000
your little value hierarchy underneath the proposition

44:14.000 --> 44:17.000
that it's up to you to work to bring the kingdom of God

44:17.000 --> 44:21.000
to life instead of hell, then maybe the whole problem

44:21.000 --> 44:24.000
of the negative meaning of life would go away.

44:24.000 --> 44:26.000
It's like you never know, beats the alternative,

44:26.000 --> 44:29.000
which is to damn the whole thing to perdition,

44:29.000 --> 44:32.000
which we really tried hard to do in the 20th century

44:32.000 --> 44:35.000
with a fair bit of success, or just to think,

44:35.000 --> 44:37.000
oh, well, this is meaningless and useless

44:37.000 --> 44:39.000
and I don't have any responsibility

44:39.000 --> 44:41.000
and there's no such thing as meaning,

44:41.000 --> 44:44.000
and it's like, sure, walk down that road, man,

44:44.000 --> 44:46.000
see where you go.

44:48.000 --> 44:49.000
Okay.

44:49.000 --> 44:53.000
It seems the both of you agree that there's this

44:53.000 --> 44:55.000
lower level meaning system that we have,

44:55.000 --> 44:58.000
which is almost like a moment to moment perceptual system

44:58.000 --> 45:01.000
where we know how to interact with things.

45:01.000 --> 45:03.000
And both of you disagree, both of you agree

45:03.000 --> 45:07.000
that there's no higher level, the meaning of life.

45:07.000 --> 45:09.000
But in alluding to the meaning crisis

45:09.000 --> 45:12.000
and just general morality, you seem to assume

45:12.000 --> 45:14.000
that we can somehow cobble this ability

45:14.000 --> 45:17.000
to know how to interact with the glass,

45:17.000 --> 45:20.000
to somehow interact with societies.

45:20.000 --> 45:24.000
So how do you think we're able to do this?

45:24.000 --> 45:27.000
First of all, to be careful,

45:28.000 --> 45:31.000
and I said there's no ultimate meaning,

45:31.000 --> 45:33.000
and like I said, I was also not saying

45:33.000 --> 45:35.000
that that means that there's no ultimate meaning

45:35.000 --> 45:38.000
because if you say a problem is poorly formed,

45:38.000 --> 45:40.000
you're rejecting both the positive

45:40.000 --> 45:42.000
and the negative answer to that question.

45:42.000 --> 45:44.000
It doesn't imply that, therefore,

45:44.000 --> 45:46.000
the ultimate meaning is that there's no meaning.

45:46.000 --> 45:48.000
It's like saying what's north of the North Pole.

45:48.000 --> 45:50.000
The answer is not anything.

45:50.000 --> 45:52.000
It's to reject the question.

45:52.000 --> 45:55.000
So I first want to challenge that move you made.

45:55.000 --> 45:58.000
Secondly, I do think that...

45:58.000 --> 46:00.000
I want to reply...

46:00.000 --> 46:02.000
I do think that what I'm trying to argue for,

46:02.000 --> 46:04.000
and I think Jordan is, but I'm not clear

46:04.000 --> 46:07.000
because he said about 17,000 things in his last thing.

46:07.000 --> 46:10.000
I want to try and reply to them.

46:12.000 --> 46:15.000
I'll spin them out, you sort of.

46:17.000 --> 46:19.000
I'm arguing for a deep continuity

46:19.000 --> 46:21.000
between those lower level processes

46:21.000 --> 46:23.000
and the highest levels.

46:23.000 --> 46:26.000
And I think Nietzsche tried to foreshadow that,

46:26.000 --> 46:28.000
and this is again what I mean about the...

46:28.000 --> 46:30.000
Nietzsche said, the height of my spirituality

46:30.000 --> 46:33.000
reaches into the depth of my sexuality.

46:33.000 --> 46:35.000
To try and find...

46:35.000 --> 46:38.000
He was using both of those in a metaphorical extension.

46:38.000 --> 46:40.000
I'm not only arguing for the lower level...

46:40.000 --> 46:43.000
It's a pretty good statement for a virgin, too.

46:48.000 --> 46:51.000
He was referring to Nietzsche, by the way, not me.

46:54.000 --> 46:57.000
So I'm arguing for what I think is a very important thesis,

46:57.000 --> 47:00.000
which is a deep continuity between the lower level

47:00.000 --> 47:03.000
and, just speaking of it metaphorically, the higher level.

47:03.000 --> 47:05.000
I do think there is an important issue

47:05.000 --> 47:08.000
in which we can talk about that higher level

47:08.000 --> 47:10.000
as distinct from the lower level

47:10.000 --> 47:12.000
of just trying to solve our daily problems,

47:12.000 --> 47:14.000
which I think is important.

47:14.000 --> 47:17.000
Namely, and that's something that I think is important,

47:17.000 --> 47:20.000
is that we can talk about that higher level

47:20.000 --> 47:22.000
of problems, which I think is important.

47:22.000 --> 47:25.000
Namely, and that's something that you referenced, Jordan.

47:25.000 --> 47:28.000
We face a perennial problem of our self-consciousness,

47:28.000 --> 47:30.000
and the problem with our self-consciousness

47:30.000 --> 47:32.000
is it means we have this enormous capacity

47:32.000 --> 47:35.000
to take a perspective on our own ability to take perspectives.

47:35.000 --> 47:37.000
I mean, one of the things about being a conscious being,

47:37.000 --> 47:39.000
and this is what I mean about a salient's landscape,

47:39.000 --> 47:42.000
is we not only know facts, like propositions,

47:42.000 --> 47:45.000
and we know how to do things,

47:45.000 --> 47:47.000
we also have perspectival knowing.

47:47.000 --> 47:49.000
This is the work I did with Leo Ferraro.

47:49.000 --> 47:52.000
We know what it is like to be a certain thing,

47:52.000 --> 47:54.000
to take a certain perspective,

47:54.000 --> 47:56.000
to take a certain stance on the world.

47:56.000 --> 47:58.000
I know what it's like to be a father.

47:58.000 --> 48:00.000
I know what it's like to be a teacher.

48:00.000 --> 48:02.000
And that perspectival knowing,

48:02.000 --> 48:05.000
of knowing what it's like to be something,

48:05.000 --> 48:07.000
is, again, this atmospheric meaning.

48:07.000 --> 48:09.000
But the thing we can do

48:09.000 --> 48:12.000
is we can take a perspective on that lower-order perspective.

48:12.000 --> 48:14.000
We can stand back and say,

48:14.000 --> 48:16.000
what does that perspective look like?

48:16.000 --> 48:18.000
Let me give you an example.

48:18.000 --> 48:20.000
I'm thirsty.

48:20.000 --> 48:22.000
And so I have a thirsting perspective on the world.

48:22.000 --> 48:24.000
Things that are watery are salient to me.

48:24.000 --> 48:26.000
Things that might contain water.

48:26.000 --> 48:28.000
You're getting thirsty right now, too, right?

48:28.000 --> 48:30.000
It becomes salient to me.

48:30.000 --> 48:32.000
But I can step back,

48:32.000 --> 48:34.000
and this was something also discovered in India,

48:34.000 --> 48:36.000
by the Buddhists,

48:36.000 --> 48:38.000
I can step back

48:38.000 --> 48:40.000
and take a look at my thirsting perspective.

48:40.000 --> 48:43.000
I can say, what's it like to be a thirsty person?

48:43.000 --> 48:46.000
And now I'm no longer thirsting,

48:46.000 --> 48:48.000
because I'm now motivated

48:48.000 --> 48:50.000
by something different than my thirst.

48:50.000 --> 48:52.000
I'm motivated by my curiosity

48:52.000 --> 48:54.000
about my lower-order thirst.

48:54.000 --> 48:56.000
And then I can step back

48:56.000 --> 48:58.000
and say, gee,

48:58.000 --> 49:00.000
what's it like to be curious?

49:00.000 --> 49:02.000
And then I can step back and wonder,

49:02.000 --> 49:04.000
what's it like to be somebody asking

49:04.000 --> 49:06.000
what's it like to be curious?

49:06.000 --> 49:08.000
And then you can step back and say,

49:08.000 --> 49:10.000
what's it like watching someone

49:10.000 --> 49:12.000
listen to someone talk about being curious about it?

49:12.000 --> 49:14.000
Exactly.

49:14.000 --> 49:16.000
That's what I'm trying to make.

49:16.000 --> 49:18.000
The point I'm trying to make

49:18.000 --> 49:20.000
is what happens is

49:20.000 --> 49:22.000
we have the capacity

49:22.000 --> 49:24.000
to very quickly

49:24.000 --> 49:26.000
move ourselves to what Nagel calls the view from nowhere.

49:26.000 --> 49:28.000
To this bird's eye

49:28.000 --> 49:30.000
or God's eye perspective

49:30.000 --> 49:32.000
on all of reality,

49:32.000 --> 49:34.000
in which we, by these recursive

49:34.000 --> 49:36.000
asking of questions,

49:36.000 --> 49:38.000
we have become deeply disengaged

49:38.000 --> 49:40.000
from our involvement with the world.

49:40.000 --> 49:42.000
We have an enormous capacity

