01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:48.000
this is associated with this idea of

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:50.000
levels too.

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:52.000
Piaget believed, and this is

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:54.000
his scientific justification for

01:01:54.000 --> 01:01:56.000
emergent morality in some sense,

01:01:56.000 --> 01:01:58.000
is that

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:00.000
it's within a Darwinian framework, again,

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:02.000
not within a Newtonian framework. So Piaget

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:04.000
had a proposition, and the proposition

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:06.000
was this.

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:08.000
You're the bully at the moment.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:10.000
Victor and I are having tea.

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:12.000
And you want us to play a different game.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:14.000
You want us to play, I don't know

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:16.000
what do you want us to play? Pull the cat's tail.

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:18.000
You're a bully after all.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:20.000
And so

01:02:20.000 --> 01:02:22.000
we don't want to play pull the cat's tail.

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:24.000
And so what do you

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:26.000
have to do? Well, you have to

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:28.000
expend a lot of time and energy

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:30.000
enforcing the game. And the reason you have to do

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:32.000
that is because we don't want to play the damn game,

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:34.000
so we're going to do everything we can

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:36.000
to stop you, to subvert it.

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:38.000
And so what that means is that you're going to

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:40.000
and we're going to expend a tremendous

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:42.000
amount of energy in a pursuit

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:44.000
where we could have picked a pursuit

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:46.000
where there was virtually no energy spent

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:48.000
or resources. So Piaget's idea

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:50.000
was that an

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:52.000
equilibrated game,

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:54.000
which is a game that everyone will play voluntarily,

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:56.000
if you pit that

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:58.000
in an open competition, you could say a Darwinian

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:00.000
competition, against

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:02.000
a disequilibrated game that requires

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:04.000
force to maintain your basic

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:06.000
totalitarian state, if you pit

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:08.000
those in a one-to-one competition or your

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:10.000
totalitarian personality, if you

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:12.000
pit them in a one-to-one competition

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:14.000
in relationship to the attainment

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:16.000
of virtually any goal across

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:18.000
multiple contexts, the equilibrated

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:20.000
game will win.

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:22.000
And that's why it's better.

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:24.000
And there's other reasons too. It's better because

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:26.000
it isn't only a solution

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:28.000
to a problem that's posed in one place.

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:30.000
It's a meta-solution

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:32.000
to a meta-problem that's posed in many places.

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:34.000
I'll just give one example.

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:36.000
Okay, so

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:38.000
you all tell your kids

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:40.000
be a good sport.

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:42.000
And your kids, being intelligent kids, think

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:44.000
well, don't we want to win this game?

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:46.000
It's like, of course

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:48.000
you want to win the game. Okay, so why can't

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:50.000
I bash the guy next to me over the head with

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:52.000
my hockey stick, as long as I don't get caught?

01:03:52.000 --> 01:03:54.000
That's a Canadian example, right?

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:56.000
So I'll tell you a story.

01:03:56.000 --> 01:03:58.000
I went to this hockey game once, and my son

01:03:58.000 --> 01:04:00.000
was playing, and that was really fun.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:02.000
And he was in a, like, the final

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:04.000
game, and

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:06.000
there was a kid on his team who was

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:08.000
he was a great hockey player, very, very good

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:10.000
hockey player. But

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:12.000
it was all him, man.

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:14.000
He had the puck he wouldn't pass, and he was

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:16.000
pretty good at scoring and so on, but he wasn't

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:18.000
playing with the team, and he was

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:20.000
playing to win. It was fine, fine, fine.

01:04:20.000 --> 01:04:22.000
So my son's

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:24.000
team lost. It was a great game. I think it

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:26.000
was, like, four to three at the end, and the

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:28.000
other team scored in the last 30 seconds or whatever.

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:30.000
And then all the kids came off the

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:32.000
ice, and the parent of this

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:34.000
one kid, who's like the little hero

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:36.000
hockey player, comes up to him, and

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:38.000
the kid had, like, smashed his stick against

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:40.000
the cement, and he was all

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:42.000
running around and cursing the referees,

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:44.000
and the father

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:46.000
came running up to him and said,

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:48.000
you were robbed. You know, you absolutely should

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:50.000
have won that. And I thought,

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:52.000
you're such an idiot.

01:04:52.000 --> 01:04:54.000
And he was, he was truly

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:56.000
an idiot, and a pathological

01:04:56.000 --> 01:04:58.000
one at that. And he was

01:04:58.000 --> 01:05:00.000
really destroying his child's soul.

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:02.000
And here's, this is

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:04.000
not funny. It's true. That is what

01:05:04.000 --> 01:05:06.000
he was doing. I saw it happen over a long

01:05:06.000 --> 01:05:08.000
time. That was just a microcosm

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:10.000
of their relationship and his attitude towards

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:12.000
the world. Now, why was that

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:14.000
wrong? It's like, the kid

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:16.000
wanted to win. It's like, yay, go

01:05:16.000 --> 01:05:18.000
man, went to win. He was a

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:20.000
really good hockey player.

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:22.000
So what was wrong with what the father

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:24.000
did? Okay. So then we step

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:26.000
back and we say, it's

01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:28.000
not important whether you win or lose. It's how

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:30.000
you play the game. So what does that

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:32.000
mean? Well, it doesn't actually

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:34.000
mean what it says, because it actually is important

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:36.000
whether you win or lose. You should be trying

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:38.000
to win. But then

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:40.000
the question is,

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:42.000
what are you trying to win?

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:44.000
Now, then that

01:05:44.000 --> 01:05:46.000
gets complicated. It's like

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:48.000
while you're trying to win

01:05:48.000 --> 01:05:50.000
being the best hockey player on your team,

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:52.000
are you trying to win that hockey game?

01:05:52.000 --> 01:05:54.000
Or are you

01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:56.000
trying to win the opportunity to be

01:05:56.000 --> 01:05:58.000
invited to play as many games as

01:05:58.000 --> 01:06:00.000
you can possibly play with as many people

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:02.000
in as many contexts as you possibly

01:06:02.000 --> 01:06:04.000
can across the entire course

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:06.000
of your life? Okay.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:08.000
That's what winning means.

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:10.000
And so the rule is

01:06:10.000 --> 01:06:12.000
don't win the

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:14.000
local and proximal event

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:16.000
at the price of being a

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:18.000
player in the multitude of

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:20.000
iterable games. That's the moral principle.

01:06:20.000 --> 01:06:22.000
You know? Don't put

01:06:22.000 --> 01:06:24.000
the cart before the horse, so to speak.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:26.000
And the reason for that is that

01:06:26.000 --> 01:06:28.000
a game is a microcosm of life.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:30.000
That's a Piagetian idea, which is why,

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:32.000
by the way, we like games and we'll watch

01:06:32.000 --> 01:06:34.000
them and we're thrilled about them and we engage

01:06:34.000 --> 01:06:36.000
in them all the time. But the game

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:38.000
isn't the issue.

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:40.000
The issue in some sense is the set

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:42.000
of all possible games.

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:44.000
And the most moral action is

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:46.000
the action that will enable you to have

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:48.000
the highest probability of winning

01:06:48.000 --> 01:06:50.000
the set of all possible games.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:06:52.000
And it's even a little more complicated than that,

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:54.000
which is you have to be

01:06:54.000 --> 01:06:56.000
a player in the set of all possible

01:06:56.000 --> 01:06:58.000
games in a manner that supports the

01:06:58.000 --> 01:07:00.000
existence of as many games as possible.

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:02.000
And that's, and so

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:04.000
you see what I mean, and human beings can do that

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:06.000
because we can go up that damn chain

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:08.000
of abstraction, right? We don't have to

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:10.000
just concentrate on this

01:07:10.000 --> 01:07:12.000
or a game of let's make

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:14.000
tea, you know? We can play these metagames

01:07:14.000 --> 01:07:16.000
and pose these metag questions.

01:07:16.000 --> 01:07:18.000
And one of Piaget's claims was

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:20.000
don't kid yourself

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:22.000
about this. There are rules.

01:07:22.000 --> 01:07:24.000
There are rules. There are rules for games.

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:26.000
There's lots that aren't playable.

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:28.000
The rule for a sustainable game is

01:07:28.000 --> 01:07:30.000
everybody wants to play.

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:32.000
Now, another rule is that some people get

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:34.000
to try to win, you know?

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:36.000
So, but obviously

01:07:36.000 --> 01:07:38.000
that's not where the abstraction level

01:07:38.000 --> 01:07:40.000
tops out. And so I love that.

01:07:40.000 --> 01:07:42.000
It's like, oh, that's so cool.

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:44.000
There's a hierarchy of moral value

01:07:44.000 --> 01:07:46.000
because that's action orientation.

01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:48.000
And it's an emergent property of the way

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:50.000
that complex systems organize themselves.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:07:52.000
They're basically dominance hierarchies, by the way.

01:07:52.000 --> 01:07:54.000
And not only that, that

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:56.000
system of organization has been around

01:07:56.000 --> 01:07:58.000
for so long, and I think it's

01:07:58.000 --> 01:08:00.000
about 400 million years,

01:08:00.000 --> 01:08:02.000
that we're actually biologically

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:04.000
adapted to that structure.

01:08:04.000 --> 01:08:06.000
Because we know that there are dominance hierarchies

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:08.000
that can sustain themselves quite nicely across time.

01:08:08.000 --> 01:08:10.000
And those usually value

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:12.000
the individual and the relationship between

01:08:12.000 --> 01:08:14.000
the individual and society.

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:16.000
And there's those that don't. And we're really

01:08:16.000 --> 01:08:18.000
adapted to the ones that do because those are

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:20.000
the ones in which we live when we live.

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:22.000
And so this is deeply biological

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:24.000
and it's also emergent at the same time.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:26.000
So it's a testament to your notion

01:08:26.000 --> 01:08:28.000
that it is

01:08:28.000 --> 01:08:30.000
necessary to be able to reconcile

01:08:30.000 --> 01:08:32.000
the local view with the ultimate view.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:34.000
And the more you can ensure that those

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:36.000
levels aren't in conflict with one another,

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:38.000
that's exactly what a Piagetian

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:40.000
equilibrating state is. Is that the union

01:08:40.000 --> 01:08:42.000
has been attained across the multiple levels

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:44.000
of hierarchical organization.

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:46.000
That's...

01:08:48.000 --> 01:08:50.000
Take that.

01:08:50.000 --> 01:08:52.000
I will take it. You know

01:08:52.000 --> 01:08:54.000
that I've always liked

01:08:54.000 --> 01:08:56.000
this argument of yours. I think it's one of your best.

01:08:56.000 --> 01:08:58.000
And

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:00.000
which is not a left handed insult of your other argument.

01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:02.000
I really like this

01:09:02.000 --> 01:09:04.000
argument. I think it's a good work.

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:06.000
And I've thought about it and I want to share

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:08.000
some thoughts I have about it with you.

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:10.000
I thought, I think that

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:12.000
and this is to allude back to

01:09:12.000 --> 01:09:14.000
Spinoza again in contrast to Nietzsche,

01:09:14.000 --> 01:09:16.000
I think

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:18.000
then again this is the platonic insight.

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:20.000
I mean because Plato of course had

01:09:20.000 --> 01:09:22.000
a metaphor also for

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:24.000
this moving up the levels. It's the metaphor

01:09:24.000 --> 01:09:26.000
of coming out of the cave into the real world.

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:28.000
And I think what I

01:09:28.000 --> 01:09:30.000
want to say is the highest level

01:09:30.000 --> 01:09:32.000
of the metagame is the game

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:34.000
because games are again things that exist

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:36.000
between us and the world, right?

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:38.000
I think the highest

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:40.000
level of the metagame is the game

01:09:40.000 --> 01:09:42.000
of intelligibility.

01:09:42.000 --> 01:09:44.000
I mean I think

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:46.000
what we have to have

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:48.000
ultimately, and this is what Habermas was

01:09:48.000 --> 01:09:50.000
on about, right? You have to have

01:09:50.000 --> 01:09:52.000
shareable intelligibility

01:09:52.000 --> 01:09:54.000
to do. That's the highest

01:09:54.000 --> 01:09:56.000
thing. We have to constantly

01:09:56.000 --> 01:09:58.000
be committed to that.

01:09:58.000 --> 01:10:00.000
That the grounding

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:02.000
normativity of all of our moral

01:10:02.000 --> 01:10:04.000
normativities is actually

01:10:04.000 --> 01:10:06.000
this normative demand make things

01:10:06.000 --> 01:10:08.000
intelligible. And I think

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:10.000
So do you think about that as a

01:10:10.000 --> 01:10:12.000
precondition for the emergence

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:14.000
of cooperative games? Yes. So it's like

01:10:14.000 --> 01:10:16.000
getting the rules straight.

01:10:16.000 --> 01:10:18.000
Getting the language by which you can

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:20.000
formulate the rules straight

01:10:20.000 --> 01:10:22.000
and using language in a very extended

01:10:22.000 --> 01:10:24.000
metaphor. And so

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:26.000
I think

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:28.000
part of the issue for us, though as human

01:10:28.000 --> 01:10:30.000
beings, is

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:32.000
that we do have this drive to

01:10:32.000 --> 01:10:34.000
get at what is, try to

01:10:34.000 --> 01:10:36.000
to get the

01:10:36.000 --> 01:10:38.000
maximal intelligibility project. And I think

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:40.000
science tries to do that in some ways.

01:10:40.000 --> 01:10:42.000
But

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:44.000
the problem is that we then

01:10:44.000 --> 01:10:46.000
and let me talk for a couple

01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:48.000
minutes on this. We hit

01:10:48.000 --> 01:10:50.000
a kind of perennial problem. We have

01:10:50.000 --> 01:10:52.000
these two different notions

01:10:52.000 --> 01:10:54.000
vis-a-vis intelligibility about what

01:10:54.000 --> 01:10:56.000
realness is. And I thought, I wanted

01:10:56.000 --> 01:10:58.000
to ask you about this because I want to know if this lines up

01:10:58.000 --> 01:11:00.000
with your chaos order thing.

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:02.000
We have one notion of

01:11:02.000 --> 01:11:04.000
realness that what to say

01:11:04.000 --> 01:11:06.000
that something is real is to say

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:08.000
that it is coherent,

01:11:08.000 --> 01:11:10.000
it is confirmed,

01:11:10.000 --> 01:11:12.000
it is coherent. Things have

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:14.000
come together, right?

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:16.000
And there's this mutual

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:18.000
fittedness. And then we also

01:11:18.000 --> 01:11:20.000
have a notion that no, what's real

01:11:20.000 --> 01:11:22.000
is what catches us by surprise.

01:11:22.000 --> 01:11:24.000
What was outside of our system

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:26.000
and that what we didn't know

01:11:26.000 --> 01:11:28.000
right? And that's when we get at reality.

01:11:28.000 --> 01:11:30.000
So we have these two notions of realness

01:11:30.000 --> 01:11:32.000
and I think we have two for very

01:11:32.000 --> 01:11:34.000
good reason by the way. I think we

01:11:34.000 --> 01:11:36.000
actually have three.

01:11:36.000 --> 01:11:38.000
Those are two of them for sure.

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:40.000
So I think what we have is we do have

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:42.000
this confirmation notion

01:11:42.000 --> 01:11:44.000
and then we have this

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:46.000
surprise notion. And science

01:11:46.000 --> 01:11:48.000
tries to pit the two against each other.

01:11:48.000 --> 01:11:50.000
So what you try to do is you try

01:11:50.000 --> 01:11:52.000
and do the theory part which is all the

01:11:52.000 --> 01:11:54.000
confirming coherence part. And then you run

01:11:54.000 --> 01:11:56.000
experiments in which the world can

01:11:56.000 --> 01:11:58.000
basically make you go, oh shit.

01:11:58.000 --> 01:12:00.000
And then you've got to, oh, right?

01:12:00.000 --> 01:12:02.000
At the level you wanted to.

